WEBVTT

00:01.711 --> 00:04.545
(Wil voice-over)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:04.588 --> 00:06.380
mankind has made weapons.

00:06.424 --> 00:08.298
[fire whooshes]
- Whoa!

00:08.342 --> 00:11.510
(Wil)
Bladesmiths have honed
and perfected their craft

00:11.554 --> 00:13.012
over thousands of years.

00:13.055 --> 00:14.930
And now,
for the first time ever,

00:14.974 --> 00:16.765
these men will go head-to-head

00:16.809 --> 00:18.600
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:18.644 --> 00:20.310
Welcome to the forge.

00:20.354 --> 00:23.272
(Wil voice-over)
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:23.315 --> 00:24.648
and a ticking clock,

00:24.692 --> 00:26.358
and by the end of three rounds,

00:26.402 --> 00:29.069
the bladesmiths must deliver
handmade weapons

00:29.113 --> 00:30.362
that are works of art

00:30.406 --> 00:33.282
as well as deadly instruments
of war.

00:33.325 --> 00:36.535
These weapons must survive
explosive tests

00:36.579 --> 00:39.913
as well as the scrutiny
of an expert panel judges.

00:39.957 --> 00:44.043
In the end, only one bladesmith
will take home $10,000

00:44.086 --> 00:46.962
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

00:47.006 --> 00:49.965
[dramatic music]

00:50.009 --> 00:52.468
♪ ♪

00:53.971 --> 00:58.015
♪ ♪

00:58.059 --> 00:59.641
(Arnon)
My name is Arnon.

00:59.685 --> 01:02.770
The first time I ever
made a blade I was 20 years old,

01:02.813 --> 01:06.065
standing guard
in the Israeli Army.

01:06.108 --> 01:09.193
(Jaime)
I'm Jaime Vining,
and I'm 28 years old.

01:09.236 --> 01:11.028
Not having trained under
a master bladesmith,

01:11.072 --> 01:14.948
everything I know is from online
research and reading in books.

01:14.992 --> 01:16.241
(David)
I'm David Goldberg.

01:16.285 --> 01:18.035
I was born and raised
in Philadelphia.

01:18.079 --> 01:21.955
My Japanese name is "Kinzan"--
means "gold mountain."

01:21.999 --> 01:24.416
(Jimmy)
I'm Jimmy.
I've been making blades,

01:24.460 --> 01:26.376
I'd say, since the sixth grade.

01:26.420 --> 01:28.045
I get
a deep personal satisfaction

01:28.089 --> 01:30.130
out of every knife I make.

01:30.174 --> 01:33.842
Gentlemen, welcome.

01:33.886 --> 01:35.761
There are three challenges
designed to see

01:35.805 --> 01:37.554
how well you can
work that forge

01:37.598 --> 01:40.849
and use tools
as time ticks down

01:40.893 --> 01:43.227
and the pressure goes up.

01:43.270 --> 01:46.814
After each round you will hand
your work off to our judges.

01:46.857 --> 01:48.690
They will decide who stays

01:48.734 --> 01:50.818
and who has to
surrender their weapon

01:50.861 --> 01:52.069
and leave the forge.

01:53.572 --> 01:54.905
Now it's time to meet
our judges.

01:54.949 --> 01:56.907
♪ ♪

01:56.951 --> 02:00.494
(Wil)
American Bladesmith Society
master smith, J. Neilson.

02:00.538 --> 02:02.621
World-renowned
rare weapons

02:02.665 --> 02:05.290
recreation specialist
David Baker.

02:05.334 --> 02:07.292
And last, martial artist

02:07.336 --> 02:11.130
and edged weapons expert
Doug Marcaida.

02:11.173 --> 02:13.465
They will decide who stays,

02:13.509 --> 02:15.551
and who has
to surrender their weapon

02:15.594 --> 02:16.760
and leave the forge.

02:18.889 --> 02:22.182
In front of you,
on your anvils, is a cloth.

02:22.226 --> 02:23.392
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:23.435 --> 02:27.020
♪ ♪

02:27.064 --> 02:32.484
(Wil)
That is a stack of six bars
of high-carbon steel.

02:32.528 --> 02:36.071
Your challenge is to forge,
from those bars of metal,

02:36.115 --> 02:39.032
a fully functioning weapon.

02:39.076 --> 02:41.785
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

02:41.829 --> 02:43.453
And this week,
because the challenge

02:43.497 --> 02:45.247
is so technically demanding,

02:45.291 --> 02:48.417
you will have four hours
to forge your blades.

02:48.460 --> 02:51.795
We have to harden it,
shape it, forge it--

02:51.839 --> 02:53.380
all this in four hours.

02:53.424 --> 02:54.965
Are you kidding me?

02:55.009 --> 02:56.550
The blades themselves
must fall

02:56.594 --> 02:58.385
within the following
size parameters.

02:58.429 --> 03:00.596
The length of the blade,
not including the tang,

03:00.639 --> 03:05.309
must be at least 11 inches,
but not more than 15 inches.

03:05.352 --> 03:08.187
And just to test
your skills even further,

03:08.230 --> 03:10.606
you must also use
a hata technique.

03:10.649 --> 03:13.901
A hata technique involves
forging multiple layers of steel

03:13.944 --> 03:16.445
into one billet,
from which you make your blade.

03:16.488 --> 03:20.574
Your hata must include
at least 12 layers of steel.

03:20.618 --> 03:23.202
Remember, gentlemen,
after this first round,

03:23.245 --> 03:25.579
one of you will be dismissed
from the forge.

03:27.416 --> 03:31.376
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your time starts now.

03:31.420 --> 03:35.714
♪ ♪

03:35.758 --> 03:38.133
(David)
Hata means grain.

03:38.177 --> 03:40.844
It means there is layers.

03:40.888 --> 03:44.181
I have an idea of how
I want to approach this.

03:44.225 --> 03:46.558
I decided
that I was gonna go

03:46.602 --> 03:50.437
right to a very formidable
hunting and fighting knife.

03:50.481 --> 03:54.399
It's a Japanese style, but I
have a wide range of skills,

03:54.443 --> 03:55.984
so I believe that my training

03:56.028 --> 03:58.654
both in Japanese and
contemporary knife making

03:58.697 --> 04:01.240
will help me stand out.

04:01.283 --> 04:02.741
(Jaime)
I would describe my
bladesmithing style

04:02.785 --> 04:03.992
as pretty rustic.

04:04.036 --> 04:05.577
So that's what I'm going with,

04:05.621 --> 04:08.747
a nice kukri small machete.
It fits the parameters.

04:08.791 --> 04:10.874
I'd love to win this competition
for my fiancé.

04:10.918 --> 04:12.501
We're getting married
in a few months,

04:12.544 --> 04:14.002
and I would love to take her
on a great honeymoon.

04:15.965 --> 04:18.382
(Arnon)
My style is a mixture
of the East and the West.

04:18.425 --> 04:22.678
Obviously I'm a westerner,
but I spent 12 years in Japan

04:22.721 --> 04:24.554
and studied
blacksmithing there.

04:24.598 --> 04:26.348
But it's a substantial chunk
of steel,

04:26.392 --> 04:28.433
and it will be
a fairly long blade,

04:28.477 --> 04:31.853
so I'm thinking well, maybe
I'll make a really big dagger,

04:31.897 --> 04:33.146
something I've seen
in my childhood,

04:33.190 --> 04:35.691
with a all-steel handle.

04:35.734 --> 04:37.276
(Jimmy)
You know,
I grew up in Texas.

04:37.319 --> 04:38.986
I was always hearing about
Jim Bowie and the Alamo,

04:39.029 --> 04:40.153
so I love the Bowie knife.

04:40.197 --> 04:41.905
It just appeals to me.

04:41.949 --> 04:44.199
Only problem is, my signature
blade is 5 inches long.

04:44.243 --> 04:45.826
This had to be
between 11 and 15,

04:45.869 --> 04:47.911
so it was out of
my comfort zone.

04:47.955 --> 04:52.165
Bladesmiths, your ten-minute
design period is up.

04:52.209 --> 04:54.710
You may now start
forging your blades...

04:54.753 --> 04:55.711
Now.

04:55.754 --> 05:00.132
♪ ♪

05:00.175 --> 05:03.677
I live a pretty traditional
Japanese lifestyle

05:03.721 --> 05:05.012
in an American setting.

05:05.055 --> 05:06.513
Gonna weld!

05:06.557 --> 05:08.932
When I do my sword making,
I have a Zen mind,

05:08.976 --> 05:13.770
so the style of life lends
to the Asian way.

05:13.814 --> 05:16.440
The challenge is to have
at least 12 layers

05:16.483 --> 05:19.026
in the hata
when we're finished.

05:19.069 --> 05:21.737
However, I can get 21 layers

05:21.780 --> 05:23.280
as quickly
as I can get 12 layers.

05:23.324 --> 05:24.489
[pounding]

05:26.410 --> 05:30.287
I have some ideas about
not using all six pieces.

05:30.331 --> 05:33.206
I'm gonna use five,
draw it out,

05:33.250 --> 05:36.918
cut it up,
stack four stacks of five,

05:36.962 --> 05:38.545
and then the single
in the middle.

05:38.589 --> 05:40.797
So I'll have 21 layers
when I'm done.

05:40.841 --> 05:42.257
It's going to make
such a strong blade.

05:42.301 --> 05:44.301
It's gonna really
be good-looking too.

05:44.345 --> 05:46.803
And odd numbers are for me.
I don't do even.

05:46.847 --> 05:48.638
♪ ♪

05:48.682 --> 05:52.893
How Dave is using the machines,
that long stance.

05:52.936 --> 05:55.604
He's got that martial arts,
Zen thing working for him.

05:55.647 --> 05:57.147
♪ ♪

05:57.191 --> 05:59.941
Unfettered mind is the samurai.

05:59.985 --> 06:01.943
♪ ♪

06:01.987 --> 06:04.279
(Wil)
We've given these guys
four hours instead of three

06:04.323 --> 06:05.655
because forge welding adds

06:05.699 --> 06:08.325
that extra wrinkle
in the competition.

06:08.369 --> 06:10.160
(Dave)
They have such a process
to go through

06:10.204 --> 06:11.745
to get everything to bind.

06:11.789 --> 06:14.081
Giving them the extra hour
gives the opportunity

06:14.124 --> 06:16.375
to do that correctly.

06:16.418 --> 06:18.752
(Jimmy)
For me, if these welds don't
stick, there's no coming back.

06:18.796 --> 06:21.046
The challenge is too tight.

06:21.090 --> 06:23.465
I saved up for 13 years
to open up my shop.

06:23.509 --> 06:25.342
Two weeks into the process,
unfortunately,

06:25.386 --> 06:26.343
I was burglarized.

06:26.387 --> 06:27.636
Got a lot of my equipment

06:27.679 --> 06:29.346
and a lot of
my custom knives stolen.

06:29.390 --> 06:32.057
If I win $10,000, it will
certainly take a lot of pain

06:32.101 --> 06:33.642
out of the $20,000 loss I took

06:33.685 --> 06:35.227
when I first started up
the shop.

06:35.270 --> 06:37.396
♪ ♪

06:37.439 --> 06:39.314
(Jaime)
I need to make sure
my welds stick,

06:39.358 --> 06:40.982
'cause if I don't create
a solid weld here,

06:41.026 --> 06:42.609
it's all over.

06:42.653 --> 06:44.778
♪ ♪

06:44.822 --> 06:46.071
So right now I'm working
part time as a farrier

06:46.115 --> 06:47.864
for a friend of mine,

06:47.908 --> 06:49.658
and I'm working part-time
as a bladesmith for myself.

06:49.701 --> 06:52.577
And my end goal would be
to be a bladesmith full-time.

06:52.621 --> 06:55.414
♪ ♪

06:55.457 --> 06:58.625
I know that I have to fuse
these pieces of steel together,

06:58.669 --> 07:00.961
and I have to take
every possible precaution

07:01.004 --> 07:02.337
to make that happen.

07:02.381 --> 07:06.508
♪ ♪

07:06.552 --> 07:09.594
You can screw up while making
a blade in many different ways.

07:09.638 --> 07:12.931
Maybe when I pull it out,
it's warped like corkscrew.

07:12.975 --> 07:16.476
Or maybe it bend like a spoon.

07:16.520 --> 07:17.769
♪ ♪

07:17.813 --> 07:19.104
(Dave)
Those welds aren't set.

07:19.148 --> 07:21.106
The other thing
that we could see happen

07:21.150 --> 07:23.358
is they get everything
ground beautifully,

07:23.402 --> 07:24.943
and then we test it,

07:24.987 --> 07:27.320
and then the welds fail
as we're testing.

07:27.364 --> 07:29.364
(Arnon)
Cannot be too short.
It cannot be too long.

07:29.408 --> 07:31.158
I have to fit
with a narrow parameters,

07:31.201 --> 07:33.618
because as you forge the steel,
it elongates and stretches,

07:33.662 --> 07:37.205
and you can't always predict
exactly how far it will stretch.

07:37.249 --> 07:38.290
♪ ♪

07:38.333 --> 07:40.125
When my daughter
was very young,

07:40.169 --> 07:43.003
she asked me for her birthday
present--she was seven,

07:43.046 --> 07:46.673
so I made her a dagger
with a 7-inch blade.

07:46.717 --> 07:49.718
If I win the prize, I'll take
my daughter and wife to Japan,

07:49.761 --> 07:50.927
where I studied my craft.

07:50.971 --> 07:52.721
(Wil)
One hour has elapsed!

07:52.764 --> 07:55.515
♪ ♪

07:55.559 --> 07:56.933
(Jaime)
So I put my billet
in the forge,

07:56.977 --> 07:58.727
and I'm waiting for it
to heat up,

07:58.770 --> 08:02.189
and I'm rotating it, making sure
it's heating up evenly.

08:02.232 --> 08:03.523
- Oh, you lost it.
- Oh, it fell off.

08:03.567 --> 08:04.941
And my rod breaks off.

08:04.985 --> 08:06.610
♪ ♪

08:06.653 --> 08:09.404
And I'm like, "Ugh, how am I
gonna get around this?"

08:09.448 --> 08:11.281
So I re-strategize.

08:11.325 --> 08:12.657
I go over to the rack of tongs,

08:12.701 --> 08:13.658
and I get back to work.

08:13.702 --> 08:15.619
♪ ♪

08:15.662 --> 08:17.329
(Dave)
More than anything,
I think he's forced himself

08:17.372 --> 08:20.123
into a much slower pace
by working with the tongs

08:20.167 --> 08:22.626
and not going over
and re-welding that stick.

08:22.669 --> 08:25.128
(Jaime)
When I'm going over to the press
or power hammer,

08:25.172 --> 08:27.130
I have less of a billet to use,

08:27.174 --> 08:29.966
so when I get it stretched out
to my desired length,

08:30.010 --> 08:31.801
I'm losing more and more metal

08:31.845 --> 08:35.388
just because I don't have
the full disposal of the rod.

08:35.432 --> 08:38.892
♪ ♪

08:38.936 --> 08:40.393
(Jimmy)
I'm checking out
the other bladesmiths,

08:40.437 --> 08:41.561
seeing how far along they are,

08:41.605 --> 08:43.313
how far behind I am.

08:43.357 --> 08:46.107
I am so screwed.

08:46.151 --> 08:48.068
I'm so far behind.
I really got to get going.

08:48.111 --> 08:51.196
♪ ♪

08:53.825 --> 08:55.325
- We got a fire on the floor.
- Broken stick.

08:55.369 --> 08:57.327
(Jimmy)
As I took the billet
off the hammer,

08:57.371 --> 08:59.579
the weld I made didn't stick,
and it fell on the ground.

08:59.623 --> 09:01.039
♪ ♪

09:01.083 --> 09:02.916
Come on.
That's such a rookie mistake.

09:02.960 --> 09:04.876
♪ ♪

09:04.920 --> 09:06.920
It's catching the floor on fire,
and I'm just like,

09:06.964 --> 09:08.213
"Oh, my God.
What am I gonna do?"

09:08.257 --> 09:10.840
♪ ♪

09:17.307 --> 09:20.267
[intense music]

09:20.310 --> 09:25.814
♪ ♪

09:25.857 --> 09:28.024
When the billet broke off the
handle and fell on the floor,

09:28.068 --> 09:29.901
I just had a hard time
picking it back up.

09:29.945 --> 09:31.611
(Wil)
Like a dog picking up a Frisbee.

09:31.655 --> 09:33.947
I'm just so off my game now.
It messed me up so much.

09:33.991 --> 09:36.074
♪ ♪

09:36.118 --> 09:38.868
It changed my mentality.
Now I got to rush everything.

09:38.912 --> 09:40.787
Now I'm no longer calm.

09:40.831 --> 09:44.499
Poor Jimmy's got the whole
Deputy Dog glove smear going on.

09:44.543 --> 09:46.042
[laughter]

09:46.086 --> 09:47.627
From here, it looks like
he grew a mustache.

09:47.671 --> 09:49.170
(Jimmy)
I'm just telling myself,
"Hey, calm down.

09:49.214 --> 09:51.006
You got plenty of time.
You can do this."

09:51.049 --> 09:52.799
♪ ♪

09:52.843 --> 09:55.677
I immediately go over there,
and I weld a new handle on there

09:55.721 --> 09:57.429
out of a thicker piece of steel.

09:57.472 --> 10:00.181
I need every second I can
to get caught back up.

10:01.685 --> 10:04.769
Two hours gone!
This is the halfway point.

10:04.813 --> 10:06.646
♪ ♪

10:06.690 --> 10:09.899
The plan is now
to bend the steel over

10:09.943 --> 10:11.610
and forge weld it again.

10:11.653 --> 10:15.614
To do that I heat up
the first forge-welded billet,

10:15.657 --> 10:17.991
and I make an incision
with a hot chisel.

10:18.035 --> 10:19.743
♪ ♪

10:19.786 --> 10:23.580
After that, I can reheat the
billet, and bend it onto itself.

10:23.624 --> 10:25.165
I have to keep heating up

10:25.208 --> 10:26.916
and keep hammering
and stretching it

10:26.960 --> 10:29.127
until I get the desired shape.

10:29.171 --> 10:30.337
It's a lot of elbow grease.

10:30.380 --> 10:35.133
♪ ♪

10:35.177 --> 10:38.637
I'm cruising along pretty well.
I'm finished grinding,

10:38.680 --> 10:40.930
getting the grit
to where I want it...

10:40.974 --> 10:42.515
Mother--
Phew!

10:42.559 --> 10:44.893
So I know that
I can make a hamon

10:44.936 --> 10:46.353
and make the sword strong.

10:46.396 --> 10:48.229
It ain't over till
the fat lady sings.

10:48.273 --> 10:50.357
(David)
So I used a Japanese technique.

10:50.400 --> 10:53.485
I resist portions of the blade
with clay.

10:53.528 --> 10:55.195
♪ ♪

10:55.238 --> 10:57.822
You're really seeing
some craftsmanship

10:57.866 --> 10:59.658
out of David
at this point.

10:59.701 --> 11:01.993
He's putting some detail
into that blade.

11:02.037 --> 11:04.579
(J.)
It's nice to see these guys
doing the extra stuff

11:04.623 --> 11:06.831
that we keep expecting to see.

11:06.875 --> 11:08.583
All the choices
that I'm making

11:08.627 --> 11:10.377
are a little
above and beyond,

11:10.420 --> 11:13.171
but it's what I do best.

11:13.215 --> 11:15.215
So it gets hot,
I quench it.

11:15.258 --> 11:16.549
Success.

11:16.593 --> 11:19.969
♪ ♪

11:20.013 --> 11:22.764
(Jimmy)
Holy cow. I've got so much more
forging to do.

11:22.808 --> 11:24.724
So I've got to hurry up,
forge it to shape,

11:24.768 --> 11:26.893
then get straight
to the grinder.

11:26.937 --> 11:31.564
Jimmy looks like he's in a
little bit of a daze over there.

11:31.608 --> 11:32.816
I mean, look at him
right now.

11:32.859 --> 11:34.109
He could be doing
something else.

11:34.152 --> 11:35.318
I agree.

11:35.362 --> 11:36.653
(Jimmy)
I'm just so off my game.

11:36.697 --> 11:38.405
I start making
stupid little mistakes

11:38.448 --> 11:39.614
that I normally wouldn't make.

11:42.285 --> 11:44.202
Okay, brother.

11:44.246 --> 11:46.913
I can't believe
how thick this knife is.

11:46.957 --> 11:48.331
♪ ♪

11:48.375 --> 11:49.916
I've got a lot
of grinding to do.

11:49.960 --> 11:53.044
♪ ♪

11:53.088 --> 11:55.547
There's 20 minutes left.
I'm hot. I'm tired.

11:55.590 --> 11:57.382
I'm sweaty. I'm dirty.

11:57.426 --> 11:59.300
This is my
make-it-or-break-it moment.

11:59.344 --> 12:00.385
I don't know
how I'm going to do this,

12:00.429 --> 12:01.553
but I'm not giving up.

12:01.596 --> 12:05.849
♪ ♪

12:05.892 --> 12:08.184
Never had to forge a blade
so quick.

12:08.228 --> 12:11.521
There's about ten minutes left
on the clock.

12:11.565 --> 12:13.982
As I plunge the blade
into the oil,

12:14.025 --> 12:15.233
and as I pull it out,

12:15.277 --> 12:16.818
I look at the blade.

12:16.862 --> 12:18.778
I might be patting myself
on my own shoulder here,

12:18.822 --> 12:20.780
but this is
one hell of a dagger.

12:20.824 --> 12:22.574
I don't have anything else
to do.

12:22.617 --> 12:27.120
I put it on the anvil, and
I go sit down and stare at it.

12:27.164 --> 12:28.246
Feel pretty good.

12:28.290 --> 12:31.291
♪ ♪

12:31.334 --> 12:33.126
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

12:33.170 --> 12:35.128
eight, seven,

12:35.172 --> 12:36.921
six, five,

12:36.965 --> 12:38.840
four, three,

12:38.884 --> 12:40.425
two,

12:40.469 --> 12:41.593
one.

12:41.636 --> 12:43.011
Your time is up!

12:43.054 --> 12:45.263
Bladesmiths, your time is up!

12:45.307 --> 12:46.973
♪ ♪

12:47.017 --> 12:51.478
I am devastated that
I just didn't do a better job.

12:51.521 --> 12:53.897
But at the same time, I'm
relieved that it's finally over.

12:53.940 --> 12:58.401
♪ ♪

12:58.445 --> 13:01.988
Gentlemen, that was
an epic round of competition.

13:02.032 --> 13:04.574
Now it's time to see
what the judges have to say.

13:04.618 --> 13:07.660
So, Jimmy, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:07.704 --> 13:12.081
♪ ♪

13:12.125 --> 13:14.250
Well, Jimmy,
I like the big Bowie profile.

13:14.294 --> 13:16.336
You looked like you here having
a little bit of trouble

13:16.379 --> 13:18.046
with your
hata technique.

13:18.089 --> 13:21.007
When the handle fell off,
it really threw me off my game.

13:21.051 --> 13:22.926
And then I was
just trying to catch up,

13:22.969 --> 13:25.428
and, you know, it just messed me
up mentally, so.

13:25.472 --> 13:26.471
But you got
your 12 layers.

13:26.515 --> 13:27.555
Yes, sir.

13:27.599 --> 13:28.890
(J.)
Was a requirement.

13:28.934 --> 13:30.558
And everything looks clean.

13:30.602 --> 13:31.559
Nicely done.

13:31.603 --> 13:33.520
Thank you.

13:33.563 --> 13:36.189
(Wil)
David, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:36.233 --> 13:40.777
♪ ♪

13:40.821 --> 13:42.695
While you were working,
we saw some interesting stuff

13:42.739 --> 13:44.280
going on
with your hata technique.

13:44.324 --> 13:45.865
Wanna tell me about it?

13:45.909 --> 13:48.993
I wanted to make four bars,
five layers each.

13:49.037 --> 13:51.538
Then I took the extra bar
and stuck it in the center,

13:51.581 --> 13:53.081
so I had 21 layers.

13:53.124 --> 13:55.458
So I chose
this cut-and-stack method.

13:55.502 --> 13:58.545
I like the shape.
Good job.

13:58.588 --> 14:01.840
Jaime, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:01.883 --> 14:07.136
♪ ♪

14:07.180 --> 14:09.138
Congratulations,
being the rookie of the group

14:09.182 --> 14:10.557
and finishing through
with a nice blade.

14:10.600 --> 14:11.558
Thank you.

14:11.601 --> 14:12.642
Tell us about your hata.

14:12.686 --> 14:14.227
(Jaime)
I got the 12 layers.

14:14.271 --> 14:15.728
A little bit of a struggle
for me

14:15.772 --> 14:17.313
because I don't forge weld
that often,

14:17.357 --> 14:18.898
so I was just happy to see
it took.

14:18.942 --> 14:21.776
Very good. Thank you.

14:21.820 --> 14:25.071
(Wil)
Arnon, please present
your weapon to the judges.

14:25.115 --> 14:30.159
♪ ♪

14:30.203 --> 14:32.912
First of all, I'm a huge fan
of the dagger design.

14:32.956 --> 14:35.498
It was nice also to see you
doing a more traditional route

14:35.542 --> 14:37.292
with your hata technique,

14:37.335 --> 14:39.836
folding, as opposed
to cut-and-stack.

14:39.880 --> 14:42.046
Yes, I'm very familiar
with that technique.

14:42.090 --> 14:43.882
And you got your 12 layers
in quickly.

14:43.925 --> 14:44.883
Yes.

14:44.926 --> 14:45.884
Nicely done.

14:45.927 --> 14:46.926
Thank you.

14:46.970 --> 14:48.511
♪ ♪

14:48.555 --> 14:50.430
(Wil)
You did an excellent job
of making this

14:50.473 --> 14:52.765
a very difficult decision
for our judges.

14:52.809 --> 14:54.309
But they need some time
to decide

14:54.352 --> 14:56.102
who's going through
to the next round

14:56.146 --> 14:57.854
and who's leaving
the forge.

14:57.898 --> 14:58.897
Thank you.

14:58.940 --> 15:06.279
♪ ♪

15:06.323 --> 15:08.281
- Well, here we go.
- Yeah.

15:08.325 --> 15:10.074
(Wil)
Let's go ahead
and start with Jimmy's blade.

15:10.118 --> 15:12.660
♪ ♪

15:12.704 --> 15:14.287
[laughs]

15:14.331 --> 15:16.080
It's really heavy.
The tang is just massive.

15:16.124 --> 15:17.457
(J.)
Very thick, yes.

15:17.500 --> 15:19.292
He's got a lot
of grinding to do

15:19.336 --> 15:21.336
to get this blade
to a finished point.

15:21.379 --> 15:24.255
It's a good shape
for a chopping cast.

15:24.299 --> 15:26.674
(Wil)
Let's move on
to David's blade.

15:26.718 --> 15:30.386
♪ ♪

15:30.430 --> 15:31.930
- Boy, is it heavy.
- Yeah.

15:31.973 --> 15:34.933
There is so much material
in that blade.

15:34.976 --> 15:36.809
Then I like what he did
with 21 layers in his hata.

15:36.853 --> 15:38.561
(J.)
That was nice, yeah.

15:38.605 --> 15:42.482
You got some, you know, cajones
there, making all these layers.

15:42.525 --> 15:45.902
But he's going to wind up
grinding 50% of that out.

15:45.946 --> 15:47.820
But it's got a good
slashing feel to it,

15:47.864 --> 15:49.530
and it's got a good belly
for the chop.

15:49.574 --> 15:52.617
We asked for the best
that they could do.

15:52.661 --> 15:54.535
I think he went
above and beyond with that.

15:54.579 --> 15:55.870
Let's move on to Jaime's blade.

15:55.914 --> 15:59.332
♪ ♪

15:59.376 --> 16:02.001
I like the design, because
it's got that straight back,

16:02.045 --> 16:03.962
which is gonna be
a good chopper.

16:04.005 --> 16:05.880
Don't like the handle.
It's a little bit big.

16:05.924 --> 16:08.091
Which, once again,
how's he going to design that

16:08.134 --> 16:09.968
so that it could feel
comfortable.

16:10.011 --> 16:12.428
Let's move on to Arnon's blade.

16:12.472 --> 16:14.263
(J.)
I mean, I enjoyed watching him.

16:14.307 --> 16:17.475
All his hammer work and doing
a traditional fold on it,

16:17.519 --> 16:20.061
and I'm a big fan
of the daggers but,

16:20.105 --> 16:21.354
I mean, there's a lot there.

16:21.398 --> 16:23.064
It's going to be
a lot to swing.

16:23.108 --> 16:26.985
The blade itself had to be
between 11 and 15 inches.

16:27.028 --> 16:29.612
There's no way
that that's 15 inches.

16:29.656 --> 16:32.115
- I think it's a bit long.
- It's longer.

16:32.158 --> 16:34.450
(Dave)
It's a full, what, 16 1/4?

16:34.494 --> 16:36.119
- I mean, this isn't 1/8 over.
- No.

16:36.162 --> 16:37.996
This isn't 1/4.
This is over an inch.

16:38.039 --> 16:39.414
That's a consideration,

16:39.457 --> 16:42.208
but is it
a disqualifying consideration?

16:42.252 --> 16:47.922
♪ ♪

16:47.966 --> 16:49.799
(Jimmy)
I'm looking around
at my competitors,

16:49.843 --> 16:52.343
and honestly, I don't think
anybody did worse than me.

16:52.387 --> 16:53.678
I think I'm going home.

16:53.722 --> 16:55.346
♪ ♪

16:55.390 --> 16:57.515
Bladesmiths...

16:57.559 --> 17:00.643
The time has come for one of you
to leave the forge.

17:00.687 --> 17:02.478
♪ ♪

17:02.522 --> 17:05.273
Arnon, you did not make the cut.

17:08.028 --> 17:10.611
Arnon, the rules were laid down
for a size,

17:10.655 --> 17:13.614
and you wound up
an inch over that length.

17:13.658 --> 17:15.158
Don't know what else
I can tell you.

17:15.201 --> 17:16.743
I understand.

17:16.786 --> 17:19.203
(Wil)
Arnon, please surrender
your weapon.

17:19.247 --> 17:21.539
I do feel a bit
of a disappointment

17:21.583 --> 17:23.374
about being eliminated.

17:23.418 --> 17:25.793
It would have been nice
to continue.

17:25.837 --> 17:29.505
In the end, that one extra inch
of blade is what defeated me.

17:29.549 --> 17:31.215
I'm just awful with numbers.

17:31.259 --> 17:35.428
So that's a very obvious thing
to get axed for.

17:35.472 --> 17:38.639
♪ ♪

17:38.683 --> 17:41.392
Gentlemen, congratulations.

17:41.436 --> 17:44.729
You've made it to round two
of our competition.

17:44.773 --> 17:46.731
Your second challenge
is to make

17:46.775 --> 17:48.941
a working fit
and finished weapon

17:48.985 --> 17:52.695
worthy of your name
and reputation.

17:52.739 --> 17:55.073
You will have three hours
for this challenge.

17:55.116 --> 17:58.451
You can use that time to address
any problems or issues

17:58.495 --> 18:00.661
that you had
with your blade in round one.

18:00.705 --> 18:03.664
But you must also
use that time

18:03.708 --> 18:06.959
to design and fabricate
a handle for your blades

18:07.003 --> 18:10.129
out of the range of material
provided for you.

18:10.173 --> 18:11.589
At the end of this challenge,

18:11.633 --> 18:13.591
your blade's
strength and durability

18:13.635 --> 18:15.676
will be tested in a wood chop

18:15.720 --> 18:18.179
as well as its ability
to hold an edge

18:18.223 --> 18:21.516
in a specially designed
sharpness test.

18:21.559 --> 18:25.019
At the end of this round,
one of you will have to go home.

18:25.063 --> 18:27.730
♪ ♪

18:27.774 --> 18:31.692
You have three hours on the
clock. Your time starts...

18:31.736 --> 18:34.112
♪ ♪

18:34.155 --> 18:35.238
Now.

18:35.281 --> 18:38.282
♪ ♪

18:38.326 --> 18:40.118
I definitely wish
I would have forged the blade

18:40.161 --> 18:41.577
a lot thinner in round one.

18:41.621 --> 18:43.538
[grinding]

18:43.581 --> 18:45.248
Because now the first thing
I've got to do

18:45.291 --> 18:46.999
is move a ton of metal.

18:47.043 --> 18:48.960
He's got a lot to do
in three hours.

18:49.003 --> 18:51.087
♪ ♪

18:51.131 --> 18:53.381
His blade has gone
into a SlimFast program.

18:53.424 --> 18:54.423
(J.)
It has.

18:54.467 --> 18:56.092
♪ ♪

18:56.136 --> 18:59.637
In only one hour, your blade,
too, can lose four pounds.

18:59.681 --> 19:01.264
♪ ♪

19:01.307 --> 19:02.640
(Jimmy)
I have so far to go.

19:02.684 --> 19:04.934
♪ ♪

19:04.978 --> 19:07.186
Doing a two-piece handle here,
with a bolster of black,

19:07.230 --> 19:09.021
and I don't really know
what this is, but it looks nice,

19:09.065 --> 19:10.106
so I'm going to go with that.

19:10.150 --> 19:12.358
♪ ♪

19:12.402 --> 19:14.527
Cutting down
the scales to length.

19:14.571 --> 19:16.612
About to drill
a hole through 'em.

19:16.656 --> 19:18.281
Jaime must not like
his thumbs very much.

19:18.324 --> 19:19.949
[laughter]

19:19.993 --> 19:21.951
(Jaime)
The trickiest part
of building my handle

19:21.995 --> 19:24.745
is if I don't align
the scales properly,

19:24.789 --> 19:27.415
I'm going to have to start
all over with a new handle.

19:27.458 --> 19:29.709
Crank it down,
it goes right through,

19:29.752 --> 19:31.252
and everything
lines up perfectly.

19:31.296 --> 19:33.754
♪ ♪

19:33.798 --> 19:35.214
(J.)
Uh-oh.

19:35.258 --> 19:37.175
Checking to make sure
nothing separated.

19:37.218 --> 19:40.344
I inspect it.
Phew! And it's fine.

19:40.388 --> 19:43.931
♪ ♪

19:43.975 --> 19:46.058
(David)
One of the criticisms
that the judges gave me

19:46.102 --> 19:48.019
was that my blade was too heavy.

19:48.062 --> 19:50.438
I'm going to have to change my
strategy, lighten up the blade.

19:50.481 --> 19:52.023
So I'm going to go
right to the grinder.

19:52.066 --> 19:53.024
♪ ♪

19:53.067 --> 19:54.817
Things are going well.

19:54.861 --> 19:57.570
And then I need to have
a platen instead of a wheel.

19:57.614 --> 20:00.072
So I go to the other side.

20:00.116 --> 20:03.576
So, Wil, Dave's got a great
system working here.

20:03.620 --> 20:05.453
He's just running from
one machine to the other.

20:05.496 --> 20:06.495
[grinding]

20:06.539 --> 20:08.039
♪ ♪

20:08.082 --> 20:11.459
Now he's going back
to the first grinder.

20:11.502 --> 20:13.794
I was offered the whole space,

20:13.838 --> 20:15.630
and I was offered
to use any tool.

20:15.673 --> 20:18.090
So this is a big blade;
there's a lot to do--

20:18.134 --> 20:20.384
making a handle, drilling holes,
putting a guard together.

20:20.428 --> 20:22.637
I need--I'll be lucky
to get my blade done in time.

20:22.680 --> 20:24.013
If the other fellas
wanted to use the grinders,

20:24.057 --> 20:25.723
they could too.

20:25.767 --> 20:27.266
It wasn't like I was pushing
them off the grinder.

20:27.310 --> 20:30.186
♪ ♪

20:30.230 --> 20:34.523
One hour, gentlemen!
You have one hour remaining!

20:34.567 --> 20:36.150
(Jimmy)
I know it's getting close.

20:36.194 --> 20:38.277
I still have an hour
to do the handle.

20:38.321 --> 20:40.446
Extremely tight,
but it's doable.

20:40.490 --> 20:42.865
(J.)
I really wish he had picked
a piece of bone or antler

20:42.909 --> 20:44.325
instead of having
a block of wood.

20:44.369 --> 20:47.453
Now Jimmy has to shape
that whole piece.

20:47.497 --> 20:50.831
The first hole I drilled,
it went pretty smoothly.

20:50.875 --> 20:54.543
As I'm drilling the second hole,
it bores into the first hole.

20:54.587 --> 20:56.212
Ugh.

20:56.256 --> 20:57.463
(J.)
Jimmy's looking
a little frustrated

20:57.507 --> 20:59.131
at the drill press
over here.

20:59.175 --> 21:00.675
I realize
it's not going to work.

21:00.718 --> 21:02.301
Crap.

21:02.345 --> 21:04.262
He seems to be
way behind everybody else.

21:04.305 --> 21:07.974
He's still got a raw block
of wood that he's dealing with.

21:08.017 --> 21:09.433
It's frustrating to me.
I'm like,

21:09.477 --> 21:11.644
"Hey, the safest and fastest way
to get this done

21:11.688 --> 21:13.813
is to go ahead
and just burn the handle on."

21:13.856 --> 21:16.649
(Dave)
It looks like Jimmy's bringing
the torch over to his table.

21:16.693 --> 21:18.651
So he's going to burn
that tang through the handle.

21:18.695 --> 21:21.279
(Jimmy)
I'm going to heat up the tang,
get it pretty hot,

21:21.322 --> 21:23.114
and slowly work the handle on.

21:26.119 --> 21:27.535
You can't control
that burn, can you?

21:27.578 --> 21:29.120
That's just it.

21:29.163 --> 21:30.746
It's fine when you've got
a lot of time.

21:30.790 --> 21:32.123
45 minutes left on the clock.

21:33.876 --> 21:35.751
This isn't going
to be pretty.

21:35.795 --> 21:37.795
(Jimmy)
I have to make this work,
or it's over with.

21:37.839 --> 21:39.672
♪ ♪

21:39.716 --> 21:40.881
Aw, come on.

21:47.640 --> 21:50.599
[intense music]

21:50.643 --> 21:52.852
♪ ♪

21:52.895 --> 21:55.062
[torch pops]
- Aw, come on.

21:55.106 --> 21:58.983
♪ ♪

21:59.027 --> 22:00.651
(Jimmy)
I couldn't think
of any other way

22:00.695 --> 22:04.697
that I could possibly
do another handle in time.

22:04.741 --> 22:07.325
I'm going to heat up the tang,
get it pretty hot

22:07.368 --> 22:09.327
and slowly work the handle on,

22:09.370 --> 22:11.829
and it will burn itself a hole.

22:11.873 --> 22:14.415
(Dave)
I know it's very traditional,
but--

22:14.459 --> 22:17.460
The traditional method
is called that

22:17.503 --> 22:19.086
because hardly anybody
does it anymore.

22:19.130 --> 22:20.254
There's a reason for it.

22:20.298 --> 22:23.007
We found a better way
to do it.

22:23.051 --> 22:27.386
♪ ♪

22:27.430 --> 22:29.722
(Jaime)
There are some divots
and imperfections in my blade.

22:29.766 --> 22:31.390
And I'm thinking
I really only have two choices

22:31.434 --> 22:32.683
with the time I have.

22:32.727 --> 22:34.518
I can go back
to the belt sander,

22:34.562 --> 22:36.729
and I can grind away
at the side of this

22:36.773 --> 22:39.065
until hopefully
the imperfections are gone,

22:39.108 --> 22:40.775
or I can start texturing it.

22:40.818 --> 22:42.902
♪ ♪

22:42.945 --> 22:45.279
I've never put this particular
pattern on a blade this long,

22:45.323 --> 22:46.906
so not quite sure
how it will turn out.

22:46.949 --> 22:48.240
♪ ♪

22:48.284 --> 22:50.159
So Jaime might
be actually fashioning

22:50.203 --> 22:52.870
a design into the blade.

22:52.914 --> 22:56.207
Either that or, like Dave just
said, maybe he's chasing a flaw.

22:56.250 --> 22:59.627
(Jaime)
It gives it a weird mirror
reflective image,

22:59.670 --> 23:02.296
so it draws your attention away
from the actual blade itself.

23:02.340 --> 23:06.717
♪ ♪

23:06.761 --> 23:08.803
(David)
I'm going for a traditional
Japanese handle shape

23:08.846 --> 23:10.554
for a hunting knife.

23:10.598 --> 23:13.057
I saw a really nice piece of
wood that was yellow and black,

23:13.101 --> 23:15.726
impregnated with plastic
so that it'll hold together.

23:15.770 --> 23:17.186
Stabilized wood, they call it.

23:17.230 --> 23:18.646
So it's time
to go to the drill press,

23:18.689 --> 23:21.440
and I start to drill,
and it grabbed the wood

23:21.484 --> 23:22.942
and flung it around...

23:22.985 --> 23:24.985
♪ ♪

23:25.029 --> 23:27.405
And slammed my finger
in between the vice.

23:27.448 --> 23:29.073
I need a Band-Aid.

23:29.117 --> 23:31.117
We've got blood in the forge.
Blood in the forge.

23:31.160 --> 23:32.868
(Dave)
You're not bleeding,
you're not working hard enough.

23:32.912 --> 23:34.620
(J.)
Tell me about it.

23:34.664 --> 23:36.997
(David)
Okay. Take your time.
Relax, Dave. Breathe.

23:37.041 --> 23:38.916
[breathes calmly]

23:38.960 --> 23:40.251
I will finish this knife,

23:40.294 --> 23:41.460
come hell or high water.

23:41.504 --> 23:42.920
♪ ♪

23:42.964 --> 23:44.505
I have a lot left to do.

23:44.549 --> 23:46.215
I'm going to work down
to the last minute.

23:46.259 --> 23:48.634
I'm sure of it.
I'm not worried. I'm focused.

23:48.678 --> 23:50.803
♪ ♪

23:50.847 --> 23:52.847
At this point, things are
starting to flow smoothly.

23:52.890 --> 23:54.682
[grinding]

23:54.725 --> 23:56.767
I believe I've done everything
the judges have asked for.

23:56.811 --> 23:58.561
I'm confident with my blade.

23:58.604 --> 24:00.312
I know it's going
to chop like a mother.

24:00.356 --> 24:02.440
♪ ♪

24:02.483 --> 24:03.441
Pretty sharp.

24:03.484 --> 24:06.569
♪ ♪

24:06.612 --> 24:08.779
Right now Jimmy's got the
"What the hell was I thinking?"

24:08.823 --> 24:09.864
going on in his mind.

24:09.907 --> 24:12.658
Forge heavy, grind thin.

24:12.702 --> 24:16.620
This is a case where he could
have drilled heavy, glued lots.

24:16.664 --> 24:19.081
- Yeah.
- At this point it'd be quicker.

24:19.125 --> 24:20.458
♪ ♪

24:20.501 --> 24:21.834
(Jimmy)
The tang's burning slowly

24:21.878 --> 24:23.919
because there's
just too much wood.

24:23.963 --> 24:25.754
All they had was
really hard woods,

24:25.798 --> 24:29.758
which is a really difficult
material to burn a handle on.

24:29.802 --> 24:32.970
(J.)
We got less than five minutes.
He's got a block of wood.

24:33.014 --> 24:34.763
Why he doesn't
grab something

24:34.807 --> 24:37.099
that's already got natural shape
to it, I have no idea.

24:37.143 --> 24:40.144
(Jimmy)
When I see that my plan's not
going the way it's supposed to,

24:40.188 --> 24:42.104
I kind of panic.

24:42.148 --> 24:44.190
♪ ♪

24:44.233 --> 24:46.275
This is just desperation.

24:46.319 --> 24:50.321
Time is so short,
and if I can get this to fit,

24:50.364 --> 24:52.573
I can still possibly
make this work.

24:52.617 --> 24:55.743
♪ ♪

24:55.786 --> 24:57.703
I take it back to the vice.
I'm hammering it on.

24:58.998 --> 25:01.373
So maybe, maybe, maybe...

25:01.417 --> 25:04.001
♪ ♪

25:04.045 --> 25:05.044
Just split it.

25:05.087 --> 25:07.213
♪ ♪

25:07.256 --> 25:10.424
And my heart just went,
"Aw, man."

25:10.468 --> 25:12.343
(J.)
This is just--
I just hate seeing this.

25:12.386 --> 25:17.014
It just hurts
to watch right now, seriously.

25:17.058 --> 25:19.058
Right now, it's
just devastation.

25:25.274 --> 25:29.443
Just wrap some tape around
and says, "There's my handle."

25:29.487 --> 25:31.237
♪ ♪

25:31.280 --> 25:32.738
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

25:32.782 --> 25:34.323
eight, seven,

25:34.367 --> 25:36.116
six, five,

25:36.160 --> 25:38.285
four, three,

25:38.329 --> 25:39.370
two,

25:39.413 --> 25:40.913
one.

25:40.957 --> 25:42.748
Time's up, gentlemen.
Time's up.

25:42.792 --> 25:44.708
Good job, man.

25:44.752 --> 25:47.878
(Jimmy)
I have failed everybody
who was rooting for me.

25:47.922 --> 25:49.380
I let myself down.

25:49.423 --> 25:52.007
♪ ♪

25:58.724 --> 26:01.684
[intense music]

26:01.727 --> 26:06.605
♪ ♪

26:06.649 --> 26:08.232
Just split it.

26:09.944 --> 26:12.528
♪ ♪

26:12.572 --> 26:14.613
Time's up, gentlemen.
Time's up.

26:14.657 --> 26:16.323
Good job, man.

26:16.367 --> 26:19.577
(Jimmy)
I have failed everybody
who was rooting for me.

26:19.620 --> 26:21.078
I let myself down.

26:21.122 --> 26:22.746
♪ ♪

26:22.790 --> 26:24.540
There was so many other
directions I could have gone.

26:24.584 --> 26:27.001
But, no, I had to do it
the way I've always done it,

26:27.044 --> 26:28.627
and that was
the wrong way to do it.

26:28.671 --> 26:33.132
♪ ♪

26:33.175 --> 26:35.426
Gentlemen, your challenge
was to forge

26:35.469 --> 26:38.762
a fully functioning weapon
of your own design.

26:38.806 --> 26:41.682
(Dave)
Jaime, there are
a couple of visible flaws,

26:41.726 --> 26:44.977
but your creativity,
the handling, the look--

26:45.021 --> 26:46.061
really enjoyed it.

26:46.105 --> 26:48.314
Thank you.

26:48.357 --> 26:52.234
(Doug)
Dave, you've got 21 layers
put in there.

26:52.278 --> 26:55.237
The handle construction--
got a signature style to it.

26:55.281 --> 26:57.239
It's a beautiful weapon.

26:57.283 --> 26:59.366
♪ ♪

26:59.410 --> 27:03.579
(J.)
Jimmy, if you'd put any kind
of rudimentary handle on this,

27:03.623 --> 27:06.123
I think this would have been
a great blade to test.

27:06.167 --> 27:07.708
I'm very disappointed.

27:07.752 --> 27:10.127
♪ ♪

27:10.171 --> 27:15.382
Jimmy, you did not complete
your weapon in round two.

27:15.426 --> 27:18.636
Your weapon cannot compete
in these challenges.

27:18.679 --> 27:21.555
Therefore,
you didn't make the cut.

27:21.599 --> 27:23.182
Doug?

27:23.225 --> 27:24.975
Jimmy,
we saw your meltdown.

27:25.019 --> 27:28.520
But if you stayed in the fight
and you put a handle in,

27:28.564 --> 27:30.898
even if it's just
to make it functional,

27:30.941 --> 27:33.317
I believe you would
probably go through.

27:33.361 --> 27:34.943
But I hope
this experience

27:34.987 --> 27:37.946
will only strengthen
your will to forge on.

27:37.990 --> 27:39.365
Thank you, sir.

27:39.408 --> 27:42.409
Jimmy, please surrender
your blade.

27:42.453 --> 27:47.539
♪ ♪

27:47.583 --> 27:49.375
The rules are pretty clear.

27:49.418 --> 27:51.877
You had to put a handle on it
to advance to the next stage.

27:51.921 --> 27:53.545
I made the wrong decision,

27:53.589 --> 27:54.922
and I dug in my heels,
instead of stopping and going,

27:54.965 --> 27:57.758
"Hey, just figure
something else out."

27:57.802 --> 27:59.927
I thought the message
that Doug gave me was very deep,

27:59.970 --> 28:02.096
and I absolutely
intend to follow it.

28:02.139 --> 28:08.477
♪ ♪

28:08.521 --> 28:11.647
David, Jaime,
congratulations.

28:11.691 --> 28:14.733
You guys have made it
to the<i> Forged in Fire</i> final

28:14.777 --> 28:18.654
and are one step closer
to $10,000.

28:18.698 --> 28:20.280
When you showed up to the forge,

28:20.324 --> 28:22.991
we asked you to create a weapon
of your own design

28:23.035 --> 28:25.035
using our tools and equipment.

28:25.079 --> 28:26.704
For this next round,

28:26.747 --> 28:28.831
we're sending you back
to your home forges,

28:28.874 --> 28:32.543
and you're going to create
a weapon of our choosing.

28:32.586 --> 28:36.130
It's time to reveal what that
mystery weapon will be.

28:36.173 --> 28:39.091
♪ ♪

28:39.135 --> 28:40.592
The katar.

28:40.636 --> 28:42.094
♪ ♪

28:42.138 --> 28:44.722
The katar is a
punching and thrusting weapon

28:44.765 --> 28:46.640
originating from southeast Asia.

28:46.684 --> 28:48.100
It was the special weapon

28:48.144 --> 28:50.394
of the fearsome Rajput warriors
from India,

28:50.438 --> 28:53.147
who were said to hunt tigers
with a pair of katars

28:53.190 --> 28:57.776
to prove their skill, bravery,
and nobility as warriors.

28:57.820 --> 28:59.737
It has a distinctive
H-shaped handle

28:59.780 --> 29:02.614
which places the large
triangular blade, or blades,

29:02.658 --> 29:05.576
directly over
the wearer's clenched fist.

29:05.619 --> 29:07.578
The experienced warrior
would use the katar

29:07.621 --> 29:09.037
like an extension of their arm,

29:09.081 --> 29:11.790
allowing for fluid,
fast, and agile attacks

29:11.834 --> 29:13.542
in much the same way
as the famous

29:13.586 --> 29:16.879
Marvel superhero Wolverine
uses his deadly claws.

29:16.922 --> 29:18.338
♪ ♪

29:18.382 --> 29:20.674
Your challenge is to forge
an authentic,

29:20.718 --> 29:23.886
fully functional version
of that iconic weapon.

29:23.929 --> 29:26.013
♪ ♪

29:26.056 --> 29:27.765
(Jaime)
I've seen a katar before.
I've seen 'em in movies.

29:27.808 --> 29:29.767
But I've never made one
so it should be pretty fun.

29:29.810 --> 29:31.852
♪ ♪

29:31.896 --> 29:33.395
I've never made a katar before.

29:33.439 --> 29:35.147
But I'm going
to knock it out of the park.

29:35.191 --> 29:36.315
♪ ♪

29:36.358 --> 29:37.983
In five days,
you will return

29:38.027 --> 29:40.861
to present your finished katar
to our judges,

29:40.905 --> 29:42.488
who will put your katars

29:42.531 --> 29:46.033
through a series of dynamic
and grueling tests.

29:46.076 --> 29:47.659
Once those tests are completed

29:47.703 --> 29:49.745
they will determine
who will be crowned

29:49.789 --> 29:52.122
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion

29:52.166 --> 29:54.124
and receive
a check for $10,000.

29:54.168 --> 29:55.751
♪ ♪

29:55.795 --> 29:57.586
I'm gonna do everything I can
to beat David.

29:57.630 --> 30:00.088
I'm gonna make sure my weapon
can pierce, slice,

30:00.132 --> 30:01.840
whatever's possible.

30:01.884 --> 30:04.426
Going home to my home forge,
I understand the tooling.

30:04.470 --> 30:06.303
I know how to use
all my machines.

30:06.347 --> 30:07.846
The cards are in my favor.

30:07.890 --> 30:09.348
The stars are aligned.

30:09.391 --> 30:10.891
This challenge is mine to win.

30:10.935 --> 30:12.226
- Good luck.
- Okay, man.

30:12.269 --> 30:17.439
♪ ♪

30:17.483 --> 30:18.816
I'm back at my forge.

30:18.859 --> 30:20.317
I'm very excited
to start my project.

30:20.361 --> 30:21.735
♪ ♪

30:21.779 --> 30:23.904
I decided to sketch
something myself.

30:23.948 --> 30:26.406
I am going with
a two-bladed katar.

30:26.450 --> 30:29.743
It's a little more unique
than your standard single piece,

30:29.787 --> 30:31.328
so I'm really hoping
that impresses the judges.

30:31.372 --> 30:34.289
♪ ♪

30:34.333 --> 30:37.376
Going up against David is going
to be a real challenge for me.

30:37.419 --> 30:38.836
I'm really going to have
to pull out all the stops,

30:38.879 --> 30:40.128
but I really think I can do it.

30:40.172 --> 30:47.511
♪ ♪

30:47.555 --> 30:50.055
I'm pumped to make this blade.

30:50.099 --> 30:53.183
I have five days.
I want to make this thing solid.

30:53.227 --> 30:54.977
I'm going to make
a seven-layer bar--

30:55.020 --> 30:58.814
one bar for every<i> budo</i> virtue.

30:58.858 --> 31:02.651
I always make a seven-layer bar
for the center of my swords

31:02.695 --> 31:06.029
because I represent<i> budo.</i>

31:06.073 --> 31:07.114
I'm a warrior.

31:07.157 --> 31:08.657
♪ ♪

31:08.701 --> 31:11.326
Five days is not enough
to make a masterpiece

31:11.370 --> 31:13.412
if you're working
at normal pace.

31:13.455 --> 31:14.830
So I ramped it up.

31:14.874 --> 31:16.248
I'm running
from forge to grinder,

31:16.292 --> 31:18.208
back to the hammer,
to the press.

31:18.252 --> 31:19.251
I'm going crazy.

31:19.295 --> 31:23.881
♪ ♪

31:23.924 --> 31:25.299
(Jaime)
Yesterday, I was able to get

31:25.342 --> 31:27.134
most of the shape of my blade
done.

31:27.177 --> 31:29.219
Today, I'm going
to finish the handle.

31:29.263 --> 31:31.054
This is actually the first time
I've ever done

31:31.098 --> 31:32.806
a handle and blade combination
like this,

31:32.850 --> 31:34.391
so we'll see how it goes.

31:34.435 --> 31:36.768
♪ ♪

31:36.812 --> 31:38.979
There's really not much metal
there to secure it,

31:39.023 --> 31:42.524
so everything needs to line up
perfectly to work out.

31:42.568 --> 31:44.526
Everything's lining up nice.

31:51.160 --> 31:52.534
Blade will be up here.

31:54.872 --> 31:57.247
My biggest concern for today
is hardening my blades.

31:57.291 --> 32:00.125
I don't exactly know what the
tempering process should be.

32:00.169 --> 32:01.752
I don't know
if it'll crack or warp.

32:01.795 --> 32:05.380
♪ ♪

32:05.424 --> 32:08.342
[sizzling]

32:14.224 --> 32:15.641
Success.

32:15.684 --> 32:17.267
Now onto the next step.

32:17.311 --> 32:19.102
♪ ♪

32:19.146 --> 32:22.397
(David)
My plan today is to bring
the steel from the blade

32:22.441 --> 32:25.692
down into the handle armatures,
and I've never done it.

32:25.736 --> 32:27.319
♪ ♪

32:27.363 --> 32:30.906
Shaping any metal takes
a lot of care and precision.

32:30.950 --> 32:32.824
It's a make-or-break-it day.

32:32.868 --> 32:40.791
♪ ♪

32:46.632 --> 32:49.257
I notice a crack
on the side of the blade.

32:49.301 --> 32:52.219
If it's in there,
it won't be good.

32:52.262 --> 32:53.762
[bleep].

32:53.806 --> 32:56.431
After all those efforts,
the blade's [bleep].

32:56.475 --> 33:00.018
♪ ♪

33:07.277 --> 33:10.612
[intense music]

33:10.656 --> 33:12.406
(David)
While I was shaping my sword,

33:12.449 --> 33:14.908
I noticed a crack
on the side of the blade.

33:14.952 --> 33:17.369
I'm not going back with
a blade that's sub-standard,

33:17.413 --> 33:19.955
so I'm gonna forge
another sword.

33:19.999 --> 33:21.456
♪ ♪

33:21.500 --> 33:25.293
I put on traditional
Japanese work uniform

33:25.337 --> 33:27.129
in order to set myself up

33:27.172 --> 33:29.506
mentally, physically,
and emotionally.

33:29.550 --> 33:30.674
It's going to be tough.

33:30.718 --> 33:32.009
I'm going to work every minute.

33:32.052 --> 33:33.468
[pounding]

33:33.512 --> 33:36.304
"Ichiban, number one,"
is what this says.

33:36.348 --> 33:38.557
There can be only one.

33:38.600 --> 33:42.060
♪ ♪

33:42.104 --> 33:43.478
(Jaime)
Today's day four.

33:43.522 --> 33:45.731
I need to attach
the blades to the handle,

33:45.774 --> 33:46.773
sharpen the blade,

33:46.817 --> 33:48.734
and do a lot of detail work.

33:48.777 --> 33:51.486
Nothing's gonna stop me
from getting this $10,000.

33:51.530 --> 33:53.196
♪ ♪

33:53.240 --> 33:56.491
Day five: gonna take
that knife out and finish it.

33:56.535 --> 33:57.492
I got ten hours.

33:57.536 --> 34:05.459
♪ ♪

34:06.795 --> 34:13.050
♪ ♪

34:13.093 --> 34:15.052
[makes whooshing sounds]

34:15.095 --> 34:16.595
[laughs]

34:16.638 --> 34:18.305
(Jaime)
My katar is as solid
as it can be.

34:18.348 --> 34:20.015
I'm happy with the way
it turned out.

34:20.059 --> 34:22.934
(David)
That's a $10,000 knife
all day long.

34:22.978 --> 34:24.603
I'm winning this thing.

34:24.646 --> 34:27.689
♪ ♪

34:27.733 --> 34:30.692
Gentlemen,
welcome back to the forge.

34:30.736 --> 34:33.904
Both had five days
to work on your katars.

34:33.947 --> 34:36.740
You were asked to do
a historical recreation,

34:36.784 --> 34:38.575
but with your signature stamp.

34:38.619 --> 34:41.787
I hope that you've done
your very best work.

34:41.830 --> 34:44.831
David, how did you put your
signature stamp on your blade?

34:44.875 --> 34:49.503
(David)
Well, I used a piece of Damascus
for the blade.

34:49.546 --> 34:52.047
I wanted something
that had an ancient feel to it,

34:52.091 --> 34:55.550
so I left it gray and polished
it up just a little bit

34:55.594 --> 34:58.345
so you could see the lines and
the veins running through it.

34:58.388 --> 35:00.055
I call it
the bull's-eye pattern.

35:00.099 --> 35:01.515
(Wil)
Great.

35:01.558 --> 35:03.475
Jaime, how did you make
this blade your own?

35:03.519 --> 35:07.020
In my research, I saw that the
katar normally had one blade.

35:07.064 --> 35:08.605
I put two blades on it.

35:08.649 --> 35:10.899
I wanted to give it
a little something extra.

35:10.943 --> 35:13.610
And I really tried to make the
whole katar a weapon, you know,

35:13.654 --> 35:16.238
from the side, from the piece
running down your forearm.

35:16.281 --> 35:17.697
I really want it
to be a weapon.

35:17.741 --> 35:19.157
♪ ♪

35:19.201 --> 35:21.159
Well, gentlemen,
both of your weapons

35:21.203 --> 35:23.537
are beautiful and intricate.

35:23.580 --> 35:26.206
But all that matters
in this competition

35:26.250 --> 35:29.709
is how they hold up
during our tests.

35:29.753 --> 35:30.710
Doug?

35:30.754 --> 35:33.964
♪ ♪

35:34.007 --> 35:36.007
To test your katar's balance

35:36.051 --> 35:38.301
and ability to slice and slash,

35:38.345 --> 35:40.846
we have created this
multilayered strike zone.

35:40.889 --> 35:44.391
It consists of different targets
at varying positions.

35:44.434 --> 35:46.351
Jaime, you're first.
Are you ready?

35:46.395 --> 35:47.394
Absolutely.

35:47.437 --> 35:55.360
♪ ♪

35:56.697 --> 36:02.993
♪ ♪

36:03.036 --> 36:04.452
Nice.

36:04.496 --> 36:07.122
Definitely's got
good swing to it,

36:07.166 --> 36:09.291
cuts through the air.

36:09.334 --> 36:10.500
As a slasher...

36:11.962 --> 36:13.545
That will cut.

36:13.589 --> 36:16.006
- Good job.
- Thank you.

36:16.049 --> 36:17.632
David, you're up.
Are you ready?

36:17.676 --> 36:18.800
I'm ready.

36:18.844 --> 36:26.766
♪ ♪

36:28.103 --> 36:34.733
♪ ♪

36:34.776 --> 36:37.694
It is a good slasher,

36:37.738 --> 36:41.656
but I wish you didn't
extend this guard here.

36:41.700 --> 36:44.451
It has some issues
turning my wrist around.

36:44.494 --> 36:45.660
♪ ♪

36:45.704 --> 36:46.828
Good balance, though.

36:46.872 --> 36:48.330
Thank you.

36:48.373 --> 36:50.457
Both of our blades
performed really well.

36:50.500 --> 36:54.002
It's anybody's game
until the fat lady sings.

36:54.046 --> 36:56.630
To test your weapon's ability
to deliver a lethal strike,

36:56.673 --> 36:59.966
I will take your weapons
to punch and thrust

37:00.010 --> 37:01.676
into this ballistic gel dummy

37:01.720 --> 37:04.304
that is wearing the kind
of Indo-Persian armor

37:04.348 --> 37:05.847
that these weapons would face.

37:05.891 --> 37:07.390
Dave, you're up.
Are you ready?

37:07.434 --> 37:08.433
I'm ready.

37:08.477 --> 37:12.229
♪ ♪

37:12.272 --> 37:14.147
I'm feeling
a little trepidatious.

37:14.191 --> 37:16.608
I'm hopeful my blade will cut
through the chain mail.

37:16.652 --> 37:24.574
♪ ♪

37:28.705 --> 37:32.707
(Doug)
Well, that went
and disemboweled him.

37:32.751 --> 37:35.919
That punctured right through
the chain mail,

37:35.963 --> 37:37.796
definitely went
right into the heart.

37:37.839 --> 37:39.464
♪ ♪

37:39.508 --> 37:40.715
That, sir, is a killer.

37:40.759 --> 37:42.592
Thank you.

37:42.636 --> 37:43.969
All right, Jaime,
you're up next. You ready?

37:44.012 --> 37:45.095
I'm ready.

37:45.138 --> 37:46.763
♪ ♪

37:46.807 --> 37:48.515
Seeing the ballistic dummy
was covered in chain mail,

37:48.558 --> 37:50.475
I'm a little concerned.

37:50.519 --> 37:53.812
The geometry of the tips of my
katar weren't really designed

37:53.855 --> 37:55.772
to get through
a piece of chain mail.

37:55.816 --> 38:03.071
♪ ♪

38:09.621 --> 38:11.746
[intense music]

38:11.790 --> 38:13.331
All right, Jaime,
you're up next. You ready?

38:13.375 --> 38:14.374
I'm ready.

38:14.418 --> 38:22.340
♪ ♪

38:29.975 --> 38:31.725
Disemboweled him there.

38:31.768 --> 38:34.686
It didn't quite
go through the chain mail.

38:34.730 --> 38:37.105
But because this splits apart,

38:37.149 --> 38:39.649
it got in a little nick
right in there.

38:39.693 --> 38:42.444
And on the final kill right
above there, it got through.

38:44.156 --> 38:45.113
Jaime, it will kill.

38:45.157 --> 38:46.614
Thank you.

38:46.658 --> 38:49.200
Two kill shots,
I was pretty happy with that.

38:49.244 --> 38:51.661
I think anybody
on the battlefield would be.

38:51.705 --> 38:53.788
♪ ♪

38:53.832 --> 38:56.041
For the strength test,
your katar will be placed

38:56.084 --> 38:58.585
in this
pneumatic arm thrusting device.

38:58.628 --> 39:01.629
This device is calibrated
so that every thrust

39:01.673 --> 39:04.424
is going to be the same
for each of your designs.

39:04.468 --> 39:07.802
And just to make it
more interesting,

39:07.846 --> 39:09.554
we've doubled the layers.

39:09.598 --> 39:12.682
Your katar will have to go
through two sheets of metal.

39:15.645 --> 39:17.771
Dave, are you ready?

39:17.814 --> 39:19.105
I'm ready.

39:19.149 --> 39:21.775
♪ ♪

39:21.818 --> 39:23.818
Three, two, one. Engage!

39:23.862 --> 39:31.785
♪ ♪

39:34.414 --> 39:35.622
Very nice.

39:35.665 --> 39:38.833
That went right through
both sheets.

39:38.877 --> 39:39.876
This blade is strong.

39:39.920 --> 39:41.169
Thank you.

39:41.213 --> 39:45.048
My blade pierces
both sheets of iron.

39:45.092 --> 39:46.716
Awesome.
Philly steel.

39:46.760 --> 39:48.510
♪ ♪

39:48.553 --> 39:50.637
Okay, Jaime, we've loaded
your katar into the device.

39:50.680 --> 39:51.721
Are you ready?

39:51.765 --> 39:52.722
I'm ready.

39:52.766 --> 39:54.224
♪ ♪

39:54.267 --> 39:56.518
In three, two, one. Engage!

39:56.561 --> 40:04.484
♪ ♪

40:06.321 --> 40:09.531
Well, Jaime, it went through
the first sheet of metal.

40:09.574 --> 40:12.742
It didn't go through
the second sheet of metal.

40:12.786 --> 40:15.954
And your alignment on the tips
are now warped.

40:15.997 --> 40:17.789
But it still went through
the first sheet.

40:17.833 --> 40:18.873
Good job.

40:18.917 --> 40:20.500
Thank you.

40:20.544 --> 40:22.335
It's really disappointing
to see that my katar

40:22.379 --> 40:24.504
didn't go through
both sheets of metal.

40:24.548 --> 40:26.798
But as far as
design and performance,

40:26.842 --> 40:28.466
I'd say
we're about neck and neck still.

40:28.510 --> 40:32.512
♪ ♪

40:32.556 --> 40:34.389
(Wil)
Jaime, David,

40:34.433 --> 40:37.559
in five days, we asked you
to forge a katar

40:37.602 --> 40:40.019
and have your own personal stamp
on it.

40:40.063 --> 40:42.439
You've both done that.

40:42.482 --> 40:46.109
But there can only be
one winner of $10,000.

40:46.153 --> 40:47.819
♪ ♪

40:47.863 --> 40:49.446
J.

40:49.489 --> 40:52.407
Well, David, I love your
one-piece design setup.

40:52.451 --> 40:55.160
You've built a lot of strength
into your blade that way.

40:55.203 --> 40:56.369
It was a very nice design.

40:56.413 --> 40:57.745
Thank you, J.

40:57.789 --> 40:59.080
I like the fact
that you kind of

40:59.124 --> 41:00.874
stayed with
a historical pattern.

41:00.917 --> 41:03.376
It's very large for the handle
you put on it.

41:03.420 --> 41:05.253
So it had the tendency
to want to

41:05.297 --> 41:07.046
kind of roll out of your hand.

41:08.633 --> 41:11.092
Overall,
a beautiful piece.

41:11.136 --> 41:12.093
Thank you, David.

41:12.137 --> 41:13.970
Comments for Jaime?

41:14.014 --> 41:16.931
(Doug)
Jaime, you're creative.
You're imaginative.

41:16.975 --> 41:18.725
And you can make it a reality.

41:18.768 --> 41:22.604
But in this forge, we will hold
you to that reality.

41:22.647 --> 41:25.273
And your split blade
didn't cut through the metal

41:25.317 --> 41:27.942
as well as
we thought it would.

41:27.986 --> 41:30.570
Jaime, it was a great
creative design you have there.

41:30.614 --> 41:33.239
The imagination that
went in to it was really cool.

41:33.283 --> 41:35.074
Big problem I have
is that one of your blades

41:35.118 --> 41:37.702
ended up being loose
during the testing.

41:37.746 --> 41:40.121
Actually, have one blade that's
flopping around a bit now.

41:40.165 --> 41:44.876
♪ ♪

41:44.920 --> 41:47.420
You've both been
outstanding competitors.

41:47.464 --> 41:50.673
However, there can only
be one<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

41:50.717 --> 41:55.512
♪ ♪

41:55.555 --> 41:59.224
David, you are
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

41:59.267 --> 42:00.308
Congratulations.

42:00.352 --> 42:01.684
[sighs]

42:01.728 --> 42:03.186
♪ ♪

42:03.230 --> 42:05.939
Jaime,
you did not make the cut.

42:05.982 --> 42:08.024
The creativity that
went in to your blade--

42:08.068 --> 42:09.526
all really, really good.

42:09.569 --> 42:11.402
But I think historically,
there's a reason

42:11.446 --> 42:13.947
that most bladed weapons
have a single blade.

42:13.990 --> 42:18.159
And that second blade just winds
up slowing everything down.

42:18.203 --> 42:22.247
And because it didn't pass the
tests as well as David's blade,

42:22.290 --> 42:23.623
that's how we made our decision.

42:23.667 --> 42:25.333
Thank you.

42:25.377 --> 42:28.044
Jaime, please surrender
your weapon.

42:28.088 --> 42:30.922
It's validating for me
to have made it this far.

42:30.966 --> 42:32.423
Thank you.

42:32.467 --> 42:34.342
Now I know
I can compete with guys

42:34.386 --> 42:35.677
that have been doing this
for 20, 30 years.

42:35.720 --> 42:37.637
- Thank you.
- All right, brother.

42:37.681 --> 42:40.557
Congratulations, David. You are
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

42:40.600 --> 42:44.143
You're gonna get a check
for $10,000.

42:44.187 --> 42:45.645
How do you feel, man?

42:45.689 --> 42:47.564
What a road.

42:47.607 --> 42:49.274
Dave, you've never made
a katar before

42:49.317 --> 42:50.942
and look what you came up with.

42:50.986 --> 42:53.570
Your Japanese masters
would be so proud of your work.

42:53.613 --> 42:54.654
Congratulations.

42:54.698 --> 42:56.364
Thank you, Doug.

42:56.408 --> 42:59.534
A 10 G purse? Phew.
It's coming at the perfect time.

42:59.578 --> 43:02.829
Thank you very much.
<i> Domo arigato gozaimashita.</i>

43:02.872 --> 43:07.208
♪ ♪
